e and fall of ancient civilizations to the afflictions of the modern psyche.Taking readers from the time of Hippocrates to the unfolding crisis of global warming today, David Livingstone reveals how climate has been critically implicated in the politics of imperial control and race relations; been used to explain industrial development, market performance, and economic breakdown; and served as a bellwether for national character and cultural collapse. He examines how climate has been put forward as an explanation for warfare and civil conflict, and how it has been identified as a critical factor in bodily disorders and acute psychosis.A panoramic work of scholarship, The Empire of Climate maps the tangled histories of an idea that has haunted our collective imagination for centuries, shedding critical light on the notion that everything from the wealth of nations to the human mind itself is subject to climate’s imperial rule.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aClimatologyxHistory. 0aEnvironmental protectionxSocial aspects. 0aHuman beingsxEffect of climate on. 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh  aAtmospheric.  aBrain.  aCausal.  aCentury.  aCivilization.  aClimate.  aClimatic.  aCold.  aColonial.  aConflict.  aContrast.  aCountry.  aCultural.  aData.  aDeterminism.  aDevelopment.  aDisease.  aDiseases.  aEconomic.  aEnergy.  aEnvironment.  aEnvironmental.  aEvolution.  aEvolutionary.  aFood.  aForces.  aGeography.  aHealth.  aHeat.  aHippocratic.  aHistorical.  aHistory.  aHot.  aHuman.  aImperial.  aLabour.  aMedical.  aMeteorological.  aMilitary.  aMontesquieu.  aMoral.  aNations.  aNature.  aPatterns.  aPeoples.  aPetersen.  aPhilosophy.  aPopulation.  aPower.  aRaces.  aRacial.  aRange.  aReaders.  aRegimes. 